A Note About the Header Landmark Solution

08

The solution that we came up with to add an H1 above the other headings on a page was to use a React Portal.

Opening up the Web Developer Toolbar and looking at the Document Outline shows us the heading structure of the Listing Detail page:

We have CampSpots as the H1, then H2s for the MegaNav buttons, and the name of the listing as another H2. Each of these H2s has small subheadings for its content.

On the Listings page, we have a similar structure to start the page: An H1 of CampSpots along with the MegaNav H2’s. For the content here, the “Listings” heading is an H2, and each individual location listing is an H3.

Because of the way the CampSpots site was originally architected, we had to use a React Portal in order to get an H1 to render above the H2s in the MegaNav.

Depending on the structure of your application, you might have to use a similar solution if you end up without an H1.

All in all, we have a great heading structure that has one H1, and all of the other headings are in order.

However, there is a bit of a problem:

Running axe DevTools, it’s going to complain that our H1 is outside of the header landmark. It’s important to note that this is a “best practice” rule and not a WCAG violation, but it still isn’t ideal.

There’s definitely a trade-off, and I don’t love the React Portal solution of injecting the H1 into the portal-root DOM node. I just am not aware of a method of injecting an H1 component into the component where the header landmark lives.

Ultimately, I decided that using the portal solution that put all of our headers in the right order was a better solution than meeting a best practice suggestion from a tool. Maybe

The best solution would be to test with users who rely on assistive tech to see how their experience is.

They may rely on headings for navigation more than landmarks. Or perhaps a different solution would emerge.
